# Feature Structure

Each feature in `src/features/` follows a consistent layered architecture.

## Required Files

Every feature MUST have these 5 files:

```
src/features/{feature}/
├── {feature}.controller.ts  # HTTP layer
├── {feature}.service.ts     # Business logic
├── {feature}.repository.ts  # Data access
├── {feature}.routes.ts      # Route definitions
└── {feature}.validation.ts  # Input validation
```

## Naming Convention

- Use singular form for feature names (e.g., `person` not `persons`)
- File names: `{feature}.{layer}.ts`
- Class names: `{Feature}{Layer}` (e.g., `PersonController`)

## Example Structure

```typescript
// person.controller.ts
class PersonController { }
export default new PersonController();

// person.service.ts
class PersonService { }
export default new PersonService();

// person.repository.ts
class PersonRepository { }
export default new PersonRepository();
```

## Type Definitions

Types go in `src/shared/types/{feature}.types.ts`:

- `{Feature}` - Database model type
- `Create{Feature}Request` - Creation input
- `Update{Feature}Request` - Update input
- `{Feature}Response` - API response format

## When Creating New Features

1. Create all 5 required files
2. Add types to `src/shared/types/`
3. Follow existing patterns from `person` or `marriage` features
4. Export singleton instances from controller/service/repository
